    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-06-09T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-06-09T13:00:00-05:00" n="192"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d192">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00/1686: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Phillips</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-06-09T19:00:00+01:00"
                            >June 9, 1939—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received June 9—4:04 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>219. During a conversation with Ciano<note n="7" xml:id="d192fn7">Count Galeazzo
                        Ciano, Italian Minister for Foreign Affairs.</note> this morning he remarked
                    apparently with confidence that Europe was entering upon a “long period of
                    peace.” In reply to my inquiry as to whether his statement included the Danzig
                    problem as well as the Italo-French difficulties he intimated that Germany had
                    no intention of pushing the former to a solution and that the Italian Government
                    was equally prepared to postpone the solution of their problems with the French.
                    There had always been unsettled problems in Europe he added and there was no
                    reason why these to which I had referred should not await their turn.</p>
                <p>The Minister is preparing to leave for Madrid on or about June 20 on a visit to
                    General Franco. He said that no military alliance between Spain and the Axis
                    powers was being considered at the present time but added that possibly it might
                    come later.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
